In the Democratic Republic of the Congo, customary divorce is often characterized by disagreements, quarrels, disputes, excommunication from family ties, segregation from the group, and powerful behavior from the women accused by the community.

Divorce is legally banned In the Democratic Republic of the Congo, although it is practiced through customary means.

Some of these customary practices are; among other things, signing of divorce documents, recognizing the divorce, moderating the conflict/behavior of the woman, and modifying habitus.

a. Bemba custom Divorce

The customs and institutions of the Bemba people (region: central), have an access website (27). Divorce is not a desirable freedom in Bemba culture; but nevertheless bears some striking elements compared to the rest of the country.

Among the Bemba, divorce has the following features; divorce may be accessed by one of three ways; onora zithi divorced when the husband disappears for a year or more, the woman that is left behind may legally divorce him, without waiting for the specified time. Another is chiimu giiki or communistic divorce, where a husband may abandon or flee to another village because he is dissatisfied, has become involved in sin, or because his wife makes him angry.
